The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Thursday, April 08, 2004 Nation Briefs				 																Shock death damages				 																																																	Akola (PTI): The Maharashtra State Electricity Board has been directed by a district court to pay Rs 3 lakh as compensation to a woman whose husband was electrocuted.				 																																																										Additional district judge M.V. Yeotikar granted the compensation to Shabanabee of Washim and directed the board to deposit the amount in the court.				 																																																										Shabanabee told the court that her husband, Kalim Khan, died of electric shock after a live wire fell on him while he was working in a field in June 2000.				 																Green bacteria				 																																																	Shimla (PTI): Scientists at the Indian Institute of Science have developed an environment-friendly method that makes use of bacteria to extract metals from minerals in the ocean bed. Scientists of the metallurgy department of the institute have used a bacteria  bacillus M1  to extract metals like cobalt, copper and nickel from nodules (metal ore) sourced from the Indian Ocean. 				 																Kids charred				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): Two children were charred to death after suspected militants set their house ablaze in Poonch on Wednesday. Sources said Labran, 8, and Tabraiz, 2, were burnt alive after the house of a Gujjar in Potha was set on fire.				 																Army clinics				 																																																	New Delhi: The army is set to open 227 polyclinics across the country, including in Calcutta and the Northeast, for ex-servicemen. An army release said this will be the biggest medical scheme for ex-servicemen. A one-time payment of Rs 5,000 to Rs 18,000 will be deducted from the pension of the army personnel, said a spokesperson of the armys medical core.
